[[File:Homestead_Temporary_Shelter_for_Unaccompanied_Children.jpg|thumb|Homestead Temporary Shelter for Unaccompanied Children in 2016.]] '''Homestead Temporary Shelter for Unaccompanied Children''' is a migrant children's detention center in [[Homestead, Florida]]. The center is currently being run by [[Comprehensive Health Services, Inc.]] (CHSi).
== About == The Homestead Temporary Shelter for Unaccompanied Children is located in [[Homestead, Florida]] and can accommodate up to 1,000 minor immigrants to the [[United States]].<ref name=":0">{{Cite news|url=https://www.miamiherald.com/news/local/community/miami-dade/article213411029.html|title=Up to 1,000 children held by immigration authorities now living in Homestead compound|last=Hanks|first=Douglas|date=18 June 2018|work=Miami Herald|access-date=2018-07-02|last2=Medina|first2=Brenda|language=en}}</ref> The Homestead Shelter was the first in [[South Florida]] to house unaccompanied minor immigrants.<ref name=":1">{{Cite news|url=https://www.miamiherald.com/news/local/immigration/article86137097.html|title=An inside look at what happens to children after crossing the U.S. border|last=Madan|first=Monique O.|date=26 June 2016|work=Miami Herald|access-date=2018-07-02|language=en}}</ref> It is located in a former [[Job Corps]] building and it is surrounded by tall fencing with security checkpoints.<ref name=":1" /> Minors in the shelter are provided with meals, snacks, medical care, recreation time and classes.<ref name=":1" /> The shelter is currently being operated by [[Comprehensive Health Services, Inc.]] (CHSi) and is being used to house minors between the ages of 13 and 17.<ref name=":3">{{Cite news|url=http://www.miaminewtimes.com/news/miami-beach-commissioner-threatens-to-punish-child-migrant-facility-contractor-10454554|title=Miami Beach Commissioner Threatens to Ban Child-Migrant Contractor From City Business|last=Iannelli|first=Jerry|date=2018-06-20|work=Miami New Times|access-date=2018-07-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.floridatoday.com/story/news/local/2018/06/20/cape-canaveral-detention-center/717375002/|title=Cape Canaveral company runs Homestead facility housing 1,000 migrant children|last=McCarthy|first=John|date=|work=Florida Today|access-date=2018-07-02|language=en}}</ref> Starting in mid-April, CHSi began to advertise around 40 new positions in Homestead.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.abcactionnews.com/news/local-news/i-team-investigates/job-postings-may-shed-light-on-life-for-unaccompanied-migrant-children-at-homestead-shelter|title=Job postings may shed light on life for unaccompanied migrant children at Homestead shelter|last=LaGrone|first=Katie|date=2018-06-22|work=WFTS|access-date=2018-07-02|language=en-US}}</ref>
In 2017, the shelter was shut down when there was no longer a need to house unaccompanied minors, but in early 2018, the shelter was reopened "without public notice."<ref name=":0" /> In February 2018, CHSi won a $30 million government contract to run the shelter.<ref name=":3" /> While most of the minors in the Homestead shelter crossed the border unaccompanied, in 2018, 94 were separated from their parents at the border under the [[Trump administration family separation policy]].<ref name=":2">{{Cite web|url=https://www.local10.com/news/florida/miami-dade/protesters-gather-outside-homestead-temporary-shelter-for-unaccompanied-children|title=Protesters gather outside Homestead Temporary Shelter for...|last=Wright|first=Madeleine|date=|website=Local 10 News|language=en-US|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2018-07-02}}</ref> On June 22, 2018, government officials were allowed to tour the facilities which had 782 boys and 387 girls on the premises.<ref name=":4">{{Cite news|url=http://www.sun-sentinel.com/news/florida/fl-reg-homestead-immigration-tour-20180622-story.html|title=Rubio, journalists tour center for migrant children in Homestead|last=Fox|first=Ben|date=22 June 2018|work=Sun-Sentinel.com|access-date=2018-07-02|language=en-US}}</ref> On average, minors remain in the shelter for around 25 days before they are placed in homes of family or friends who live in the U.S.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://abcnews.go.com/US/reporters-notebook-inside-florida-shelter-immigrant-children/story?id=56090422|title=Reporter's Notebook: Inside a Florida shelter for immigrant children|last=Withers|first=Scott|date=2018-06-22|website=ABC News|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2018-07-02}}</ref>
== Criticism == Protestors who were upset about the [[Trump administration family separation policy]] demonstrated in front of the Homestead shelter on June 20, 2018.<ref name=":2" /> The previous day, [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] politicians, state representative, [[Kionne McGhee]], Senator [[Bill Nelson]] and Congresswoman [[Debbie Wasserman Schultz]], were denied entry to the shelter which led to protesters "accusing the Trump administration of trying to cover up mistreatment."<ref name=":4" /><ref name=":5">{{Cite news|url=http://www.sun-sentinel.com/news/politics/fl-reg-shelter-inspections-20180628-story.html|title=Watchdog to scrutinize shelters for migrant kids, including 3 in South Florida|last=Swisher|first=Skyler|date=28 June 2018|work=Sun-Sentinel.com|access-date=2018-07-02|language=en-US}}</ref> Senator [[Marco Rubio]] was allowed to visit Homestead on June 22, though he did not describe what he saw.<ref name=":4" />
A government watchdog agency, the Office of Inspector General for the [[United States Department of Health and Human Services|U.S. Department of Health and Human Services]], is looking into allegations of [[Sexual abuse|sex abuse]] and extortion in the Homestead shelter.<ref name=":5" /> == References == <!--- See http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Footnotes on how to create references using <ref></ref> tags, these references will then appear here automatically --> {{Reflist|30em}}
